Turkey broadens its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey became a member of the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate the interior of this country.
In the eastern part of the Bosporus, perhaps only 20 steps inland Asia, lies one of the most interesting relics of disastrous imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha train station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least, this is what the guides say.
The building is at the end of the platforms and has two towers in front, one for each corner, resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building in your complex is a bit decadent.
But once the vault box office was over, there is no doubt what the greatness of the company was that this was the westernmost door.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a "latecomer" in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that was curated up to Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Because of the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell under the control of the United States.
British rule and when the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was bad for Hyderpasha station as well.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources said it was sabotage.
Since then the station has decayed and remained on the margins of history.
But today, this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves – at least symbolically – to highlight Turkey’s willingness to broaden its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
There is now a new partnership policy.
The Turkish government maintains excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I climbed on a bunk bed and went to the Turkish capital Ankara, in order to visit one of the leaders of the AKP, an expert on foreign policy, Turkish Prime Minister Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a jolting trip, which produced the cadences of the ancient world in the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - a new city, designed to rule a new secular state, far from the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its clear Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has raised some suspicions in the West, and especially in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the headquarters of the AKP, an ultra-modern stone-and-steel structure – built ad hoc – in a developing suburb, surrounded by half-built shopping malls and “power pies” where middle-class managers in business suits – men and women – meet first thing in the morning to agree/do business.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician of almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
“The aim of the party’s foreign policy is to re-integrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
The Cold War was an anomaly,” he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off in relations with its interior.
Today you have to look both east and west at the same time.
It is not a case if it is not towards one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "Turkey might be forced to choose?"
"Turkey," he replies, "doesn't want to affront that choice."
He goes on to underline a point that almost everyone I have spoken to up to that point had recited to me almost by heart: the relations that Turkey has not only with the Middle East, but with the Caucasus region, and with the entire Black Sea, represent a benefit for Europe and the United States as well as for Turkey itself.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe in its complex can metaphorically assemble those railway lines that open up the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Once again at Hydarpasha station, after a second sleepless night, my thoughts turn to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had attended the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How much would they have been surprised to learn that Europe’s ambitions in the Middle East would, in large part, be in Turkey’s hands today?
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back through the Bosporus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe."
So, there is not much doubt in what continent this fascinating country must claim.
