The 'bee car' that prevents collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, specifically, by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, prevents accidents.
This is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C which is the first step in collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technical Center have developed this tiny robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan’s four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to reinforce the collision-prevention capability of the brand’s vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that closely resembles the Nissan Safety Shield.
But the most important thing is the compound eyes of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allowing it to fly without interruption within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, the engineers designed what they have called a laser locator (Laser Range Finder).
It detects obstacles up to two meters away within a 180-degree radius in front of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor that immediately results in collision prevention.
“The moment it detects an obstacle, the tiny robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at right or greater angles to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the avoidance maneuver is entirely instinctive.
If it wasn’t, the robot wouldn’t be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Lab and lead engineer on this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot deflect up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot avoids collisions.
“This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It doesn’t require saving information or intuitive logic from previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with just a couple dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we’re not talking about gigas of memory, or even megas.”
This is the first step in developing new instant collision prevention technologies, a technology Nissan predicts will be introduced to standard cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the variety of lithium ions.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the way.
