EU doubles trade with India
As the European Union and India are reciprocal trading partners, this issue in addition to the other mostly global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
Today there will also be a Franco-Indian summit, to deal mainly with cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognizes that India is a great democratic developing power that should have more voice and vote in international affairs but the member countries have not yet been able to come to a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This issue has not been addressed at the ninth summit that began yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, President-in-Office of the EU, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission and Javier Solana, the main representative of foreign policy, received Manmohan Singh, Prime Minister of India with whom they reached an agreement to double in five years, that is, increase to more than one hundred billion euros, their commercial exchange.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 the exchange of goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an excessively ambitious goal.
They thus legally harmonized the existing twenty-six bilateral civil aviation conventions with India, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India until the end of 2009 wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union.
