Found the plane of Steve Fossett the millionaire disappeared a year ago
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris has been found on a 3000-meter high plateau in the Nevada highlands area of Mammoth Lakes on the California-Nevada border.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Wood County Sheriff John Anderson has dispelled the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squadron, and now we have the confirmation that it is typical of what Steve Fossett was flying on the day of his disappearance," he said in a statement.
No human remains have been found either on the plane or in the vicinity.
The billionaire, 63, was presumed dead in February.
The U.S. Office of Transportation Security (NTSB) has reported that a few hours after the sighting of the remains, a squad of investigators has been sent to identify the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, scattered since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, always in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal remains have been found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
These are two documents bearing Fossett’s name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
The search for Fossett had been interrupted a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had won a place in history thanks to a long series of firsts.
In 2002, by the sixth attempt, he had become the first Man to complete the turn of the world in a hot air balloon: two solitary weeks of flight.
Three years later he had made the turn of the world by plane and nonstop.
Among his records, also that for having flown to 15,445 meters di height, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
